        <h1>Scales &amp; Modes</h1>
        <p class="kicker">The diatonic system, the major and minor families, chromaticism, and the seven modes that grow out of the major scale.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Musical Scales</h2>

      <h3>Diatonic Scale System</h3>
      <p>Western music is built on the diatonic scale system, which consists of seven notes within an octave. The most common scale is the major scale, followed by its relative minor. These scales are characterized by specific patterns of whole and half steps, which create the distinctive sound and character of each.</p>

      <h3>Major and Minor Scales</h3>
      <p>The major scale is constructed with a pattern of whole steps and half steps (W–W–H–W–W–W–H), while the minor scale has different patterns for its natural, harmonic, and melodic forms. Major scales are often associated with brightness and positivity; minor scales with sadness or melancholy.</p>

      <figure class="diagram-figure">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 280 110" class="keyboard-svg" role="img" aria-label="Piano keyboard, one octave, with C major scale highlighted.">
