        <span class="step-cell gap-w">W</span>
        <span class="step-cell note">B</span>
        <span class="step-cell gap-h">H</span>
        <span class="step-cell note">C</span>
      </div>

      <h3>Chromaticism and Modes</h3>
      <p>Western music also uses the chromatic scale, which includes all twelve pitches within an octave — natural and altered alike. The modes (Ionian, Dorian, Phrygian, Lydian, Mixolydian, Aeolian, Locrian) offer alternative tonalities within the diatonic system, adding variety and color.</p>

      <h3>Equal Temperament</h3>
      <p>The tuning system known as <strong>equal temperament</strong> is a hallmark of Western music. It divides the octave into twelve equal intervals, allowing for flexible modulation and consistent tuning across all keys.</p>

      <h3>Historical Development</h3>
      <p>Western music has seen many scales and tuning systems over time. Early music used modes such as Gregorian chant in the medieval period. The Renaissance brought the rise of major and minor scales, leading to the tonal system that dominated Western music until the 20th century.</p>

      <h3>Influence on Global Music</h3>
      <p>Western scales and tonal systems have had a significant impact on music around the world, influencing scale development in many cultures. Many non-Western traditions have adopted aspects of Western tonality while retaining their unique character.</p>

      <h2>Types of Scales</h2>
      <p>In Western music, the notes used within scales are typically represented by the letters A, B, C, D, E, F, and G, organized in ascending order and repeated at each octave. The arrangement of these notes determines the type of scale.</p>

      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Major Scale <em>(do, re, mi, fa, sol, la, ti)</em></dt>
        <dd><span class="mono">C – D – E – F – G – A – B – C</span></dd>

        <dt>Natural Minor Scale</dt>
        <dd><span class="mono">A – B – C – D – E – F – G – A</span></dd>

        <dt>Harmonic Minor Scale</dt>
        <dd><span class="mono">A – B – C – D – E – F – G♯ – A</span> — the seventh raised by a half step.</dd>

        <dt>Melodic Minor Scale (ascending)</dt>
        <dd><span class="mono">A – B – C – D – E – F♯ – G♯ – A</span> — sixth and seventh raised when ascending; the natural minor descending.</dd>

        <dt>Chromatic Scale</dt>
        <dd><span class="mono">A – A♯ – B – C – C♯ – D – D♯ – E – F – F♯ – G – G♯ – A</span></dd>
      </dl>

      <figure class="diagram-figure">
