      <p>These notes form the foundation of melodies, harmonies, and chord progressions. Through varied combinations and arrangements, composers create the rich tapestry of sounds and expressions found in Western music.</p>

      <h2>Modes</h2>
      <p>Scale modes are variations of the major scale (the Ionian mode) that start on different degrees of the scale. Each mode has its own unique sound and characteristic intervals. The Dorian mode starts on the second degree of the major scale (D–E–F–G–A–B–C–D); the Phrygian on the third (E–F–G–A–B–C–D–E); and so on through the seven.</p>

      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Ionian</dt>
        <dd>The standard major scale. Bright and happy. Common in many genres.</dd>

        <dt>Dorian</dt>
        <dd>Starts on the second degree of the major scale. Minor quality with a major sixth — somewhat melancholy but uplifting.</dd>

        <dt>Phrygian</dt>
        <dd>Starts on the third degree. Distinctly minor, characterized by its flattened second.</dd>

        <dt>Lydian</dt>
        <dd>Starts on the fourth degree. Bright and dreamy, with a raised fourth compared to the major scale.</dd>

        <dt>Mixolydian</dt>
        <dd>Starts on the fifth degree. Bluesy, slightly jazzy, with a flattened seventh.</dd>

        <dt>Aeolian</dt>
        <dd>The natural minor scale. Starts on the sixth degree. Dark and moody.</dd>

        <dt>Locrian</dt>
        <dd>Starts on the seventh degree. Diminished quality due to flattened second and fifth. Rare in traditional tonal music.</dd>
      </dl>

      <p>Each mode carries its own intervals and characteristic colour, useful for setting different moods. Understanding modes adds depth and variety to composition and improvisation alike.</p>

